parameters.description: Log mortality rate for juvenile COTS (age 0-2 years), representing high early-life mortality of 80-90% annually

parameters.description: Log mortality rate for adult COTS (age 2+ years), representing lower adult mortality of 30-50% annually consistent with 3-7 year lifespan

parameters.description: Log baseline maturation rate at reference temperature, representing transition from juvenile to adult stage. This is the rate at temp_ref_maturation, modulated by temperature via Q10_maturation
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log baseline maturation rate at reference temperature controlling transition from juvenile to adult mortality regime (year⁻¹)

parameters.description: Log Q10 temperature coefficient for COTS maturation rate. Q10 represents the factor by which maturation rate increases per 10°C temperature increase. Typical values for ectotherm development are 2.0-3.0, with initial value of 2.5 representing moderate temperature sensitivity
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log Q10 coefficient for temperature-dependent maturation (dimensionless). Controls how strongly temperature accelerates or decelerates COTS development and sexual maturation

parameters.description: Reference temperature for baseline maturation rate. This is the temperature at which maturity_rate_base applies without temperature modification. Set near mean regional SST (~27°C for GBR)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Reference temperature for baseline COTS maturation rate (°C)

parameters.description: Optimal sea surface temperature for fast-growing Acropora coral growth. Acropora species typically have higher thermal optima than massive corals, with peak growth around 28°C on the GBR
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Optimal temperature for fast-growing coral growth rate (°C)

parameters.description: Optimal sea surface temperature for slow-growing massive coral growth. Massive corals (Porites, Faviidae) typically have slightly lower thermal optima than Acropora, with peak growth around 27°C
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Optimal temperature for slow-growing coral growth rate (°C)

parameters.description: Log thermal sensitivity parameter for fast-growing coral growth rate. Controls the width of the thermal performance curve - higher values mean growth declines more rapidly away from optimal temperature. Acropora are generally more thermally sensitive than massive corals
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log thermal sensitivity of fast coral growth (°C⁻²), controls steepness of thermal performance curve

parameters.description: Log thermal sensitivity parameter for slow-growing coral growth rate. Controls the width of the thermal performance curve. Massive corals are generally more thermally tolerant (broader curve) than Acropora
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log thermal sensitivity of slow coral growth (°C⁻²), controls steepness of thermal performance curve

parameters.description: Sea surface temperature threshold above which fast-growing Acropora corals experience bleaching-induced mortality. Acropora typically bleach at approximately 1°C above local summer maximum (~28.5°C on GBR), making 29.5°C a realistic threshold for mortality onset
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Bleaching mortality threshold temperature for fast-growing corals (°C). Above this temperature, thermal stress mortality begins to accumulate exponentially

parameters.description: Sea surface temperature threshold above which slow-growing massive corals experience bleaching-induced mortality. Massive corals (Porites, Faviidae) are more thermally tolerant than Acropora, with bleaching thresholds typically 1-1.5°C higher
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Bleaching mortality threshold temperature for slow-growing corals (°C). Higher than fast corals due to greater thermal tolerance of massive coral morphologies

parameters.description: Log baseline bleaching mortality rate for fast-growing Acropora corals when temperature exceeds bleach_threshold_fast. Initial value of 0.0 corresponds to 1.0 year⁻¹ (exp(0) = 1), representing moderate mortality that scales exponentially with thermal anomaly severity
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log baseline bleaching mortality coefficient for fast corals (year⁻¹). Determines mortality rate at threshold temperature before exponential scaling

parameters.description: Log baseline bleaching mortality rate for slow-growing massive corals when temperature exceeds bleach_threshold_slow. Initial value of -0.7 corresponds to 0.5 year⁻¹ (exp(-0.7) ≈ 0.5), representing lower mortality than Acropora due to greater thermal tolerance
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log baseline bleaching mortality coefficient for slow corals (year⁻¹). Lower than fast corals reflecting greater resilience of massive coral morphologies

parameters.description: Log steepness parameter controlling exponential increase in bleaching mortality with thermal anomaly severity. Initial value of 0.7 corresponds to 2.0 °C⁻¹ (exp(0.7) ≈ 2.0), meaning mortality approximately doubles for each 1°C above threshold. This captures the non-linear accumulation of thermal stress (analogous to Degree Heating Weeks concept)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log exponential scaling coefficient for thermal stress mortality (°C⁻¹). Controls how rapidly mortality increases with temperature above bleaching threshold. Shared between coral types as thermal stress accumulation dynamics are similar
